author: Douglas C. Meeks
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on September 29, 2018
review_content: SEE UPDATE BELOWNOTE: I have used these filters for over 7 years Filtrete Clean Living Basic Dust AC Furnace Air Filter, MPR 300, 20 x 25 x 1-Inches, 6-Pack with no problems and I keep my fan on my HVAC on 24/7 which reduces hot/cold spots and results in less dust but it means you have to change your filter more frequently but with 3 dogs in addition to the normal dust/dirt/lint they still last 4-6 weeks easy. I have reviewed other brands for Amazon and none work any better, most worse and no real cost saving on any of them.I was not going to write a review of this but after reading some of the other reviews it seemed like there was a big lack of knowledge about these filters. Let me start with the photos that people have posted (not sure if everyone's page looks like mine, should be off to the right side) and you can see one of the filters shown has a latticework design to hold/support the filter, what you may not realize is that you have essentially blocked at least 10% of your filter with that latticework, another filter shows it torn up and even a glance indicates it was inserted upside down (these filters are 1 way devices, hence the arrows on the sides showing airflow PLUS if inserted correctly the wire mesh would prevent this from happening under any circumstance). I also read about this filter being too hard on a unit... uh this is the bottom line of these filters with the least resistance to airflow and if they are hard on your unit, you may have a cheap unit or a fan about to die. I was particularly boggled by the one where the filter turned black, stopped up and collapsed and the reviewer blamed the filter ....... sounds like some serious and possibly dangerous air quality problems that need attention quickly, this is NOT a filter problem, possibly a furnace problem. As far as the thickness of material used 5 years ago vs what is used today, the thickness means nothing, it is the permeability of the material to block passage of dust/dirt and other things harmful to the unit and yes Virginia they have actually made the filter better over 5 years and probably saved themselves some money in the process. Don't lose sight of the big picture, "Does it filter as it should and have the strength to hold up?" the answer is yes, I don't care how much profit they made as long as I can buy them at a fair price in comparison to other filters and they actually do the job they promised to do (also a yes) while meeting the MPR 300 specification which is approximately equivalent to a MERV 7 (still a yes).I should note that several people mentioned the filter "bowing" when under pressure, mine stays bowed since I run my fan 24/7 and none have ever failed in 7+ years, it can flex which means it is actually less likely to break apart. The "bowing" is not a sign of failure and if it actually did come loose it would mean you have either the wrong size filter or a defective bracket in your unit since the cardboard frame remains rigid.UPDATE:  I needed to add that IF you let your filter go without replacement for much longer than its intended life and it gets so dirty it cannot pass air it can actually bow to the point it can break loose, you have to really ignore it for a LONG time and have enough trash/dirt to prevent airflow, this is a rare occurrence but I thought I should mention it.  These type filters are meant to be replaced on a regular basis.I saw no reason to take a picture of my dirty filter but it catches all the dog hair and during shedding seasons I might have to change it in 4 weeks but usually they last for about 6 weeks, I have another home in the country and those last closer to 8 weeks (which concerns me a bit about air quality in the city).I should mention that if you had your fly-by-night installer put in a "cheaper than dirt" system the list of possible problems is endless and they are never going to come back and say "it was the cheap system I installed" or "I installed it incorrectly" and the filter is always an easy target. Sadly life tends to lean towards the maxim of "You get what you pay for"Bottom Line: Ignore the horror stories, I have had many talks with several HVAC techs and the one thing they do all agree on is this:Unless you have a real need for high levels of filtering (severe allergy etc) use the filter with the least resistance that will block damaging dirt and dust from your unit (that would be this filter) and any higher level of filtering will probably shorten the life of your unit and can make the likelihood of the unit freezing up in the summer more likely due to reduced airflow over the coils. 4 Stars instead of 5 mainly because the shipping packaging seems to be a crap shoot, most times they arrive perfect but I have had several delivered where the filters were near unusable due to being crushed in a inadequate shipping box that lacked protection.
title: Ignore Any Horror Stories, Actual Info About This Filter and Filters In General UPDATE APR 2019

author: Chris
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on March 10, 2019
review_content: First of all this are not the same filters as the picture (see the photos). They create too much of a pressure drop and the furnace cycles on and off every 10 minutes. author: Shawn Reed
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on December 15, 2018
review_content: We buy a lot of furnace filters and have used expensive as well as inexpensive brands.  Had not tried the 3M Filtrate brand because it was usually out of our price range.  So when I found them at a reasonable price on Amazon I bought a half dozen.  They are the cheapest, flimsiest, gnarled up mess of filters I have ever bought.  No cross bracing to keep the filters from bowing or give you a hand hold to insert them.  And because they are so poorly supported none of the filter material ripples (ridges) are straight or even.  Whether that will impact their filtering capability is yet to be seen.  Certainly not the quality you would expect from a 3M product and not a purchase we will make again.

author: thebrietstuff
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on December 13, 2018
review_content: I was excited to purchase these filters, as they were cost effective so I could afford to replace them more often. I put the first one in shortly after receiving them a little less than a month ago. It looked fine and fit as expected in my furnace. Fast forward a few weeks, and my house is cold. I have the thermostat set at 69 & the house won't get above 62. I double checked all my windows and doors. I adjusted the thermostat. I was at a loss. As a last ditch effort before an HVAC appointment, I checked the filter (that I had replaced only a few weeks ago) & found it jammed in the furnace, with the wires bowed. When I finally got it out, I saw the filter was damaged and plugging the intake. I replaced it with a different filter and within an hour my house was warm again. Spend a few extra bucks and get a different filter! Not worth the extra stress and potential danger of a defective air filter.

I asked my husband to change the filter because of it and when I got a different filter out of the box I noticed that the filter doesn‚Äôt even have consistent coverage with the fibers and that some parts I could see right through! which means it‚Äôs not going to filter anything and dust is just going to continue blow around my house and into our faces. author: RP Meggs
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on October 24, 2019
review_content: Filtrete is a quality name in filters, everyone knows that. I bought these for the brand, size and price. What I want to point out is this: These are not the thick, heavy pleated type filters. They are thin and allow a lot of air to pass through. Which at first I thought might not be a good thing but after watching a ton of HVAC youtube videos I found out it's actually a very good thing. The high airflow makes my heat pump operate more efficiently and avoids problems like the coils icing on the heat exchanger. I use my Alexa device to remind me to replace it every month (also super important). That way I'm avoiding the two most common issues with air handlers: dirty filters and filters that restrict airflow. Just wanted to pass what I learned along. These aren't expensive but they are the proper type and won't cause issues while still getting the job done right. Hope this info helps!
title: Low Restriction Filters Avoid Air Handling Issues

author: D. Adams
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on September 30, 2019
review_content: And by cheap I mean cheaply made and very poor quality.  Per the pictures they looked very similar to the Purafilter 2000 filters I'd been purchasing elsewhere.  Since I always forget to have extras on hand, I figured this package would be a good bulk one to have.  So I got both 14x20 and 16x25 filters.  Of course, I simply went by the rating and didn't bother skimming over the actual reviews.First off, as others are saying, they do not match Amazon's photos.  Both 14x20 and 16x25 looked very different with what appears to be thin plastic (almost like hot glue) over the pleats vs metal.  They also have no rigidity to them what so ever.  I struggled for a bit trying to get it installed, having it waning to fold on me (plus it seemed thicker than my previous Purafilter.)However, what really did it in for me was the air-flow arrow.  Maybe these are designed differently but as others have mentioned, they appear to be backwards.  Perhaps this is the reason some people are talking about their units cycling often or overheating.  The short time I had mine installed, it sounded as if the filter was clogged.Needless to say, these were quickly removed from my HVAC system and I ran up the street to get what I knew worked well...

author: Andrew
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on May 8, 2019
review_content: In every other disposable furnace filter I've ever used, the support grating looks like metal chicken wire and when installed the grating goes on the side where the blower fan is.  The grating usually prevents the actual filter media from getting pulled towards the blower.These have it the other way and don't use metal.  There's thin strips of plastic every 1/8" going from one side to the other and the plastic strips appear to be melted to the filter media at every pleat.  The attachment of the plastic strips to the filter media is quite strong in my limited and unscientific tests.  It should work fine but I was confused at first because the air flow arrow on the frame appears to be pointing in the wrong direction compare to every other filter I've ever used, but I'm pretty sure the arrow is correct, this is just a new way of supporting the filter media.Other than that, it's a basic filter.  The size is almost exactly the claimed size which is nice as it fits more snugly into my furnace.  Some of the cheap filters are up to 1/4" thinner than claimed and 1/2" less in width and height, but these aren't like that.UPDATE July 8th 2019: After only 2 months installed in my furnace the first filter frame has bent along the bottom edge, see pics.  I've never had a filter bend like this.  These filters have a very weak frame.  I'll be changing them out every 1 month now until I use up the pack of them then not buying this style filter again.  Sadly it's getting harder and harder to find basic low restriction filters which aren't cheap junk, even with the 3M branding on them.
title: Mechanically weak, frame bent after only 2 months

author: Charles
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on October 20, 2019
review_content: I have been using/buying this 3M MPR 300 filters for more than 5 years for the HAVC system in my house.  The recent purchase in Oct, 2019. I found out this filter was modified with the orange plastic grids from metal grids. My first impression was 3M is trying to cost down the products to make more profit. Okay, no big deal, then I further noticed that the flow direction was marked opposite.....I am very sure the flow direction is opposite.  The flow direction is supposed to be from the filter membrane side to the filter grids side.  All other brands and including the previous model had this design, which makes more sense.  I  carefully looked at the filter membrane and can't find any much difference from previous model although some reviews said this new filter had caused restricted airflow. I will first use this new filter in the next change and observe any performance. Will come back and update.

date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on July 1, 2020
review_content: Great 3M quality and price, I waited to see how they work before reviewing. They work great! The thing to know is that  they are using a new filter support design. These strips are attached to every pleat every inch or two and will face away from your blower, the airflow arrows are correct on the package. This seems to be the problem some people are having.  If installed backwards the pleats will collapse when the blower comes on and cause airflow problems. Installed correctly the Pleats keep their shape and everything works fine.  I don‚Äôt know why they redesigned it I‚Äôm sure it‚Äôs a money-saving thing but it is what it is. These are still great filters, I will happily reorder these.

review_content: So I just had a new high efficiency furnace installed in November 2019. With the new furnace I received 3 filters. The first thing he asked was if I had changed the filter on a monthly basis. I told him yes and in fact just put a new one in yesterday.The fault was an airflow differential fault so he removed the filter and reset the furnace. Walla the furnace stayed running and warmed the house. So after the furnace kicked off he reinstalled this garbage filter and turned the thermostat up to call for heat again. BANG furnaces kicked off with the airflow differential fault again within a minute!!!Took filter out and it worked perfect again. He went back to his shop and picked up the correct size filter and tried it again. Worked fine!Long story short he said these filters restrict the airflow too much for high efficiency furnaces. Do not buy them as the material is thick and poorly constructed. These filters cost me double in the service call than I paid for this bulk packSo if you have a new high efficiency furnace stay away from these!
title: Cause ‚Äúshort cycling‚Äù and airflow fault in high efficiency furnaces

author: Todd
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on July 20, 2020
review_content: I'm not sure if I got a bad batch of these or what.  I purchased the same last year which lasted me the summer without any issues.  AZ summer, the AC runs a lot.. Purchased the same 6 pack for this summer and I've had nothing but problems.  I've had the AC unit freeze up twice so far this summer.  When it runs with these in, the house is not cooled very well.. The AC unit will run pretty much constantly and struggle to keep the house at 80F.  You can clearly hear them struggling to suck the air through - It's almost like the fabric was installed the wrong way on these.Yes, I have installed them correctly.. There are arrows clearly marking which way they should go.  The issue persisted through all 3 sets of these I've installed so far this summer.  I've had 2 different HVAC companies out this summer and neither found anything else wrong.I get the 'bowing' that others have described where it looks like they're getting sucked into the ceiling.  I also get lots of noise from these.. When the unit turns on, you can sortof hear the filters flop up into the intake and then there is a constant air sucking noise.  The house does not cool efficiently.. I have hot and cold spots when these are in.. To the point where I had to setup floor fans to blow the cool air from the cool rooms into other areas of the house.I finally remembered to pick up just a couple of the cheapest air filters they had at the grocery store the other day just to try out.. Installed those and it's like a night and day difference.  The new ones are pretty much silent.  The house cools way more evenly.  And the AC is not running constantly trying to keep up.1 star for value for money.. They appear to be the cheapest air filters on Amazon, but who knows how much extra they've cost me in cooling costs so far this year.  My electric bill is $50-70 more per month so far this summer compared to last.2 stars for ease of installation.. yeah they're easy to install, but the fabric appears to have been put on backwards? review_content: Not worth the lower price. There is nothing to prevent the filter from getting sucked in toward the flow of air. verified: Size: 20 x 30 x 1Style: Without Air PurifierVerified Purchase

author: Lewis A Edge Jr
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on August 27, 2020
review_content: Our home's forced-air heat pump system uses one air filter this size and four 14"X14"X1" filter for its air intake/return vents.  When I noticed that the vents began making an almost whistling sound, I realized that the original filters had become clogged with dust.  These replacements arrived from Amazon a day sooner than promised and were a "breeze" to install.One feature about these filters that I noticed were the corrugated elements that greatly increase their surface area compared to the filters that were installed originally.  Not surprisingly air flow through these new filters is much quieter and there is obviously less strain on the blower motor.  I'm guessing that these filters will last longer than the original filters that were installed, but they certainly resulted in quieter air flow.
title: Quieter Operation Than Original Filters

author: Chris P. Bacon
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on December 7, 2020
review_content: Audible feedback from a filter??  I've used a lot of filters in the HVAC intake of the smallish (1,245 sq ft) condo that I live in. I have a Nest brand thermostat that always prompts you to change the filters every 30-days. My residence is also in a rather rural area of the central Texas hill country that seasonally has quite a bit of dust from the cedar trees (Ashe Juniper) and oaks, plus I have a cat, so I'm fine with changing the filters more frequently. The first time I used these it became obvious that after about 30-days, they start getting rather (noticeably) noisy from whatever amount of air restriction occurs. I view this as proof that they are more effective than bargain brand filters. Your mileage may vary, but I'm am quite pleased.
title: Remarkable performance when compared to cheaper filters, with one AMAZING feature (read on)

author: r.fondo
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on December 6, 2018
review_content: I was looking for a filter that Prime would ship to our home in bulk as we need to change it every month. Our air guy recommended a mid-grade filter so the system wouldn't be overworking to push air through. I trust the Filtrete brand and was even happy to get a deal on the 6 pack! Use subscribe and save for even bigger savings!
title: Great Value to Price and Name brand too

author: Wayne C.
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on July 25, 2020
review_content: When I opened the pack, I was surprised to find there was no familiar steel wire support of the actual filter, which made me wondering whether the filter would last long enough (although you are suppose to change it every 3 months). Considering this is a fairly large size filter, the pressure created by air flow, especially after some dust build up, will be quite a bit. The one I replaced, which is also a 3M, did have solid steel wire backbone.Maybe it was my bad luck. Out of six, there was one was the side squeezed and distorted. This will cause air leak through without filtering. Another reason I was disappointed that 3M removed the steel wire support at the back. With the steel wire support, this won't happen.This is certainly one of the cheaper ones made by 3M, so probably I got what I paid for.
title: no steel wire support anymore

author: Steven B. Katz
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on December 18, 2019
review_content: After extensive research into the almost infinite number of choices (manufacturers, characteristics, MERVs, and other comments), I settled on this GM brand of filters ( bought four sizes), which had one of the best ratings from customers. I always read the worst reviews first to see what people complain about before making a decision. In this case, I made the right decision. One complaint was that these filters came damaged; mine were sent inside three tight boxes, and although they're packaged six together, this is not a problem because I put the unused ones back into one of the boxes. Another complaint was that these filters were flimsy, so much so that they got sucked up by their HVAC unit; I found these GM Filtrate filters to be as sturdy as any other, including Honeywell, even though they did not have cross-beams on the outside (perhaps larger ones than 16x20x1 would get sucked up in a furnace; my house uses these filters in the wall, not the furnace, which has its own filter installed by our HVAC company). Yet another complaint was that filters with high MERVs were so thick that they stopped the air flow, and their HVAC unit strained to circulate air; I got just the right MERV with this product, including some allergen and pollen protection--but not too much/too high as to impede airflow.  I made the right decision, and am extremely happy with this product. Given the number of opinions out there, I wanted people to know my experience. I will buy and use these GM Filtrate filters for the life of the house (or me, which ever dies first :).  Great product!
title: This is a great product

author: Taylor Walker
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on October 25, 2020
review_content: I've lived in my house for 20 years and have been ordering these same filters since I moved in and got Amazon Prime membership.- Product i'm used to:  air filter that had thin but metal backing on the back side of the filter- Last 2 orders (@ 6 filters each) have had a more flimsy looking plastic backing instead of the more firm metal. it almost looks like hot glue strands.I've read that heavy duty filters can shorten the lifespan of your furnace and that most furnaces aren't sealed in such a way that would allow these hyper filtering filters to function properly in the first place.  My furnace appears to be such a furnace.  The place you put the filter in is not an air tight seal.  That being said, filters that can stop dust, dirt, hair and other particles from getting into your units but still have decent air flow can help prolong the life of your system.  Since my furnace is still running like an absolute champ 20 years later, this must count for something.Anyway, the filters seem to work just fine, though the recent change in the product has me a little concerned since the firm metal backing now seems to be replaced with hot glue gun strands.  So far, they still seem to work as the previous ones have.  I'll edit the review if I notice these strands snapping/breaking.
title: Seems fine.  Change in product recently

verified: Size: 20 x 30 x 1Style: Without Air PurifierVerified Purchase

author: Tom Z.
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on August 23, 2020
review_content: First, these are about the lowest effective filtration you can or should buy. That's not bad, but these are basic, and will keep the big chunks of stuff from clogging up your AC coil. So if you just want to say you have a filter these fit that need.Second and most importantly, the filter media seems to have a significant pressure drop, after only a month of use. This is unusual, and I have never experienced problems before, but these were serious.With nothing else changing, I used the first of six filters, and in a little over a month, my AC condenser unit (the outside part) froze up.  That usually is caused by air flow inside being low, and that's caused by a clogged filter. Sure enough, I changed the filter and that fixed it. Same thing happened again a month later. Now I've been in this house for 6 years and routinely get 3 to 4  months without any problems, changing filters because I remember to. I cheaper out on these new ones, and regret it. For whatever reason, the material these are made of is easily restricted and really reduces air flow. Nothing else changed, no contsruction dust, dirt etc.I would not recommend these at all.  I've switched back to a better filter, the next step up like a MERV 10 or better (these are 5 which is marginal at best) and with that step up the filter material is significantly higher quality.  I'm not sure why they are so different, but they are.  Buying these was a waste of money so spend about 10% more and get something that works and won't likely freeze up your AC system, which can damage it and cost a lot of$$ to fix.
title: Low $ cost but problematic - skip these

review_content: All Filtrete ‚ÄúBasic‚Äù MPR 300 filters sold are not the same,I have been getting brown edged Filtrete MPR  300 ‚ÄúBasic‚Äù filters from my local big box store for years. author: Jared G.
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on December 4, 2020

author: Chris Harvey
date_of_review: Reviewed in the United States on March 25, 2020
review_content: The arrow on the filter points in the wrong direction. The arrow should point *towards* the wire mesh, so that when the air flows through the filter, the fibers get trapped by the wire mesh and don't leak into your home. If you install the filter according to the arrows shown, you'd be installing it backwards. If that happens, you could damage your HVAC unit by letting dust particles and fibers flow into the unit. This is really bad especially for customers who don't know any better. Just remember: Install the air filter with the metal wire side on the "clean side", facing *toward* the HVAC unit! Filtrete, you need to fix this right now.
title: Arrows point in wrong direction.

So if you get these and they collapse on you it is because you  put it in backwards because they arrow is labeled wrong. Otherwise good filters so far.
